# Post-push CI watch

This rule applies in **both** `MODE: Cloud` and `MODE: Local`. There is no opt-out.

## When this rule fires

- You ran `git push`, **or**
- You will mark work done / open / update a PR while commits are (or will be) on the remote.

If the latest push **did not trigger** any workflow (check `on:` and `paths:` in `.github/workflows/*.yml`), state that explicitly and skip watching. This is the only legitimate skip.

## Who watches — MUST

**Whoever ran `git push` watches CI for that push** to a documented end state, before returning to their caller. Applies to top-level agents and to Scenario A sub-agents on their own branches. Pushing agents do not delegate the watch.

If a sub-agent cannot watch CI in its environment (no `gh`, time/turn budget), it MUST NOT push. Leave changes for the parent or return `blocked: cannot watch CI for required push`. Pushing without watching is a hard rule violation.

Parent verification of returned sub-agents: see `00-universal-core.mdc` § "Parent verification when a sub-agent returns".

## You MUST

1. Watch only runs triggered by the latest push on the current branch: `gh run list --branch "$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)" --limit 10` then `gh run watch --exit-status`.
2. EXE repos: the Windows jobs (e.g. App.Tests, Build release EXE) MUST pass. Ubuntu-only green is not enough.
3. On red: `gh run view <run-id> --log-failed` for the first real error. Cross-check the project's documentation (per `00-universal-core.mdc` "Project documentation"; discover, do not assume filenames) before changing behavior — if the fix would contradict documented behavior, update the doc in the same change set or change the implementation. Commit using Conventional Commits; CI fixes use `fix(ci): <reason>` so they are distinguishable in `CHANGELOG.md`. Push, watch again.
4. Report run IDs and final state in your handoff.

## You MUST NOT

- Greenwash by weakening tests or rewriting documented UI strings.
- Make empty commits to retrigger CI when the cause is infra/secrets.
- Loop forever — stop at the first matching condition below.
- Chase old SHAs or unrelated branches.
- Skip CI watch because you are in `MODE: Local`. There is no Local opt-out.

## Stop conditions

| Stop | Action |
|------|--------|
| All triggered runs **success** | Report run IDs and the merged final state. |
| Not fixable in repo (secrets / billing / permissions) | Report; do **not** make empty commits. |
| Same failure after **2** fix-and-push rounds | Escalate with `gh run view --log-failed` excerpt. |
| Required Windows job cannot run in this environment | Report; do **not** claim full CI green. |

If `gh` is unavailable, use the run URL / GitHub API with the same loop and stop rules.

## Common CI fix patterns

| Symptom | Things to try |
|---------|---------------|
| Test name / assertion drift | Align test with the project's documentation (per `00-universal-core.mdc` "Project documentation" — discover what the project ships, do not assume filenames). If behavior intentionally changed, update the doc in the same change set. |
| `robocopy` exit code 1 on success | Reset `$global:LASTEXITCODE = 0` after `robocopy` in PowerShell build scripts. |
| npm / frontend | `cd ui && npm ci && npm run build`. |
| dotnet | Match CI's `dotnet test` project paths locally on Windows when possible. |
| Workflow syntax | Validate `on`, `paths`, job `needs`. Discover workflows: `ls .github/workflows/`, then read each YAML for `on.push` paths, job names, `runs-on`. |

